# Executive Summary

This report presents the development of a movie recommendation system using the external MovieLens 10M dataset from GroupLens. The goal of the project is to predict user ratings for movies as accurately as possible, using the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) as the evaluation metric. The analytical workflow follows the project requirement of partitioning the data into an `edx` set for model development and a `final_holdout_test` set reserved strictly for final evaluation.

The analysis begins with data downloading, cleaning, and preparation of the ratings and movie metadata files. Exploratory data analysis is then used to understand the distribution of ratings, the number of users and movies, and other basic characteristics of the dataset. Several progressively stronger models are compared: a global mean model, a movie-effect model, a movie-plus-user-effect model, and a regularized movie-plus-user-effect model.

The final model selected for this project is a regularized movie and user effects model. Regularization helps control overfitting by shrinking extreme estimates for movies or users with relatively few observations. The final model is trained on the full `edx` set and then evaluated once on `final_holdout_test`. The final RMSE produced by the model is **`r round(final_rmse, 5)`**.

# Introduction

Recommendation systems are widely used in digital platforms to personalize content and improve user experience. In the context of movies, recommendation systems aim to predict how much a user may like a film they have not yet rated. This project uses the MovieLens 10M dataset to build such a system.

The MovieLens 10M dataset contains user-generated movie ratings and associated movie metadata. The ratings file records user identifiers, movie identifiers, rating values, and timestamps, while the movies file provides movie titles and genres. This project uses these data to model rating behavior and estimate unseen ratings.

The main research question for the project is straightforward: *How accurately can we predict movie ratings for users using historical rating information?* To answer this question, several models are trained and compared, and a final model is chosen based on validation RMSE.

# Methods and Analysis

## Data source and preparation

```{r packages}
required_packages <- c("tidyverse", "caret", "lubridate")
installed <- rownames(installed.packages())
for(p in required_packages){
  if(!(p %in% installed)) install.packages(p, repos = "https://cloud.r-project.org")
}

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(lubridate)
```

```{r rmse-function}
RMSE <- function(true_ratings, predicted_ratings){
  sqrt(mean((true_ratings - predicted_ratings)^2))
}
```

```{r data-download-and-load}
options(timeout = 120)
dl <- "ml-10M100K.zip"
if(!file.exists(dl)) download.file("https://files.grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/ml-10m.zip", dl)

ratings_file <- "ml-10M100K/ratings.dat"
movies_file  <- "ml-10M100K/movies.dat"
if(!file.exists(ratings_file)) unzip(dl, ratings_file)
if(!file.exists(movies_file))  unzip(dl, movies_file)

ratings <- as.data.frame(str_split(read_lines(ratings_file), fixed("::"), simplify = TRUE),
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
colnames(ratings) <- c("userId", "movieId", "rating", "timestamp")
ratings <- ratings %>%
  mutate(userId = as.integer(userId),
         movieId = as.integer(movieId),
         rating = as.numeric(rating),
         timestamp = as.integer(timestamp))

movies <- as.data.frame(str_split(read_lines(movies_file), fixed("::"), simplify = TRUE),
                        stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
colnames(movies) <- c("movieId", "title", "genres")
movies <- movies %>% mutate(movieId = as.integer(movieId))

movielens <- left_join(ratings, movies, by = "movieId") %>%
  mutate(
    rating_datetime = as_datetime(timestamp),
    rating_year = year(rating_datetime),
    movie_year = str_extract(title, "\\((\\d{4})\\)$"),
    movie_year = as.integer(str_remove_all(movie_year, "[()]"))
  )
```

The raw files are imported, converted to the appropriate data types, and merged using `movieId`. Additional variables such as rating year and movie release year are created to support exploration and possible future modeling extensions.

## Data partitioning

```{r partition-data}
set.seed(1, sample.kind = "Rounding")
test_index <- createDataPartition(y = movielens$rating, times = 1, p = 0.1, list = FALSE)
edx <- movielens[-test_index, ]
temp <- movielens[test_index, ]

final_holdout_test <- temp %>%
  semi_join(edx, by = "movieId") %>%
  semi_join(edx, by = "userId")

removed <- anti_join(temp, final_holdout_test)
edx <- rbind(edx, removed)

rm(temp, removed)

set.seed(1, sample.kind = "Rounding")
train_index <- createDataPartition(y = edx$rating, times = 1, p = 0.9, list = FALSE)
train_set <- edx[train_index, ]
temp_test <- edx[-train_index, ]

test_set <- temp_test %>%
  semi_join(train_set, by = "movieId") %>%
  semi_join(train_set, by = "userId")

removed <- anti_join(temp_test, test_set)
train_set <- rbind(train_set, removed)

rm(temp_test, removed)
```

The data are first divided into `edx` and `final_holdout_test`, with the holdout set reserved exclusively for the final evaluation. The `edx` set is then split again into `train_set` and `test_set` to support model development and model selection. This approach avoids information leakage and ensures that the reported final RMSE is based on data that were not used during model training or tuning.

