## Modeling approach

The project compares four models of increasing complexity:

1. **Global mean model**: predicts every rating using the same overall average.
2. **Movie effect model**: adjusts the global mean by a movie-specific bias.
3. **Movie + user effect model**: adds a user-specific bias to account for individual rating tendencies.
4. **Regularized movie + user effect model**: applies shrinkage to the movie and user effects in order to reduce overfitting.

The regularized model is defined conceptually as:

\[
\hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_i + b_u
\]

where \(\mu\) is the global average rating, \(b_i\) is the movie effect, and \(b_u\) is the user effect. Regularization is applied when estimating the movie and user effects.

```{r baseline-and-regularized-models}
rmse_results <- tibble(Model = character(), RMSE = numeric())

# 1. Global mean model
mu <- mean(train_set$rating)
pred_mean <- rep(mu, nrow(test_set))
rmse_results <- bind_rows(rmse_results,
                          tibble(Model = "Global mean",
                                 RMSE = RMSE(test_set$rating, pred_mean)))

# 2. Movie effect model
movie_avgs <- train_set %>%
  group_by(movieId) %>%
  summarize(b_i = mean(rating - mu), .groups = "drop")

pred_movie <- test_set %>%
  left_join(movie_avgs, by = "movieId") %>%
  mutate(pred = mu + b_i) %>%
  pull(pred)

rmse_results <- bind_rows(rmse_results,
                          tibble(Model = "Movie effect",
                                 RMSE = RMSE(test_set$rating, pred_movie)))

# 3. Movie + user effect model
user_avgs <- train_set %>%
  left_join(movie_avgs, by = "movieId") %>%
  group_by(userId) %>%
  summarize(b_u = mean(rating - mu - b_i), .groups = "drop")

pred_movie_user <- test_set %>%
  left_join(movie_avgs, by = "movieId") %>%
  left_join(user_avgs, by = "userId") %>%
  mutate(
    b_i = ifelse(is.na(b_i), 0, b_i),
    b_u = ifelse(is.na(b_u), 0, b_u),
    pred = mu + b_i + b_u
  ) %>%
  pull(pred)

rmse_results <- bind_rows(rmse_results,
                          tibble(Model = "Movie + user effect",
                                 RMSE = RMSE(test_set$rating, pred_movie_user)))

# 4. Regularized movie + user effect model
lambdas <- seq(0, 10, 0.25)
rmses <- sapply(lambdas, function(l){
  b_i <- train_set %>%
    group_by(movieId) %>%
    summarize(b_i = sum(rating - mu) / (n() + l), .groups = "drop")

  b_u <- train_set %>%
    left_join(b_i, by = "movieId") %>%
    group_by(userId) %>%
    summarize(b_u = sum(rating - mu - b_i) / (n() + l), .groups = "drop")

  pred <- test_set %>%
    left_join(b_i, by = "movieId") %>%
    left_join(b_u, by = "userId") %>%
    mutate(
      b_i = ifelse(is.na(b_i), 0, b_i),
      b_u = ifelse(is.na(b_u), 0, b_u),
      pred = mu + b_i + b_u
    ) %>%
    pull(pred)

  RMSE(test_set$rating, pred)
})

lambda_results <- tibble(lambda = lambdas, RMSE = rmses)
lambda_opt <- lambda_results %>% arrange(RMSE) %>% slice(1) %>% pull(lambda)
best_dev_rmse <- lambda_results %>% arrange(RMSE) %>% slice(1) %>% pull(RMSE)

rmse_results <- bind_rows(rmse_results,
                          tibble(Model = paste0("Regularized movie + user effect (lambda = ", lambda_opt, ")"),
                                 RMSE = best_dev_rmse))
```

```{r lambda-plot}
lambda_results %>%
  ggplot(aes(lambda, RMSE)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkgreen") +
  geom_point(color = "firebrick") +
  labs(title = "Regularization Tuning Curve",
       x = "Lambda",
       y = "RMSE") +
  theme_minimal()
```

# Results

## Development results

```{r development-results-table}
rmse_results %>% arrange(RMSE)
```

The model comparison shows a clear progression in predictive performance. The global mean model provides a simple baseline but ignores meaningful variation across users and movies. Adding movie effects improves accuracy because some films tend to be rated higher or lower than average. Adding user effects improves performance further because some users consistently assign higher or lower ratings than others.

The strongest development model is the regularized movie and user effects model. This model balances flexibility with protection against overfitting by shrinking unstable estimates. The value of lambda is selected based on the smallest RMSE on the development test set.

## Final evaluation on the holdout set

```{r final-model-and-holdout-rmse}
mu_final <- mean(edx$rating)

b_i_final <- edx %>%
  group_by(movieId) %>%
  summarize(b_i = sum(rating - mu_final) / (n() + lambda_opt), .groups = "drop")

b_u_final <- edx %>%
  left_join(b_i_final, by = "movieId") %>%
  group_by(userId) %>%
  summarize(b_u = sum(rating - mu_final - b_i) / (n() + lambda_opt), .groups = "drop")

final_predictions <- final_holdout_test %>%
  left_join(b_i_final, by = "movieId") %>%
  left_join(b_u_final, by = "userId") %>%
  mutate(
    b_i = ifelse(is.na(b_i), 0, b_i),
    b_u = ifelse(is.na(b_u), 0, b_u),
    predicted_rating = mu_final + b_i + b_u
  )

final_rmse <- RMSE(final_predictions$rating, final_predictions$predicted_rating)
final_rmse
```

The final RMSE on `final_holdout_test` is **`r round(final_rmse, 5)`**.

This result indicates that the final model predicts ratings with substantially lower error than the simplest baseline model. In practical terms, the use of movie and user effects captures much of the systematic variation in the data, while regularization improves generalization to unseen ratings.

