# Conclusion

This project developed and evaluated a recommendation system using the MovieLens 10M dataset. The analysis showed that more informative models consistently outperformed simpler baselines. The best-performing model in this project was a regularized movie and user effects model, which was selected using a validation split derived from the `edx` dataset and then evaluated once on the held-out test set.

The strengths of this modeling strategy are its interpretability, computational efficiency, and solid predictive performance. However, the approach also has limitations. It does not incorporate richer forms of signal such as genre interactions, rating time trends, implicit feedback, or latent factor structure. As a result, there is still room to improve performance by using more advanced recommendation techniques.

Future work could extend the analysis by adding genre-specific effects, temporal effects, matrix factorization approaches, or hybrid models that combine collaborative and content information. Additional evaluation metrics such as MAE, Precision@K, or Recall@K could also provide deeper insight into recommendation quality beyond point prediction accuracy.

